INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '1e196e43-37aa-4407-9dbb-950302599442',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Astro State Management — URL and Loaders Beat useState for Filters and Pagination$escape$,
  $escape$Astro pages are server-rendered by default, which means the right place for filter and pagination state is the URL — not a client-side signal or useState call. Use `Astro.url.searchParams` in your `.astro` component's frontmatter to read query params directly on the server, then pass the results as props to your islands. This keeps the page shareable, bookmarkable, and SSR-consistent without any client hydration cost.

For data fetching, Astro's frontmatter IS your loader. Fetch filtered data there using `searchParams.get('page')` or `searchParams.get('category')`, then render the result statically. If you're using Astro DB or an adapter like Drizzle, query inside frontmatter and pass typed props down — no `useEffect`, no loading spinners, no client state.

Reserve client-side state (via Nano Stores or framework signals) only for genuinely ephemeral UI state — open/close toggles, hover effects. Filters and pagination belong in the URL so Astro's server rendering can own the data layer entirely.$escape$,
  $escape$---
// src/pages/blog.astro
const url = Astro.url;
const page = Number(url.searchParams.get('page') ?? '1');
const category = url.searchParams.get('category') ?? 'all';

const posts = await db
  .select()
  .from(postsTable)
  .where(category !== 'all' ? eq(postsTable.category, category) : undefined)
  .limit(10)
  .offset((page - 1) * 10);
---

<PostGrid posts={posts} currentPage={page} category={category} />$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
