INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b10be05b-9aae-45db-bc0f-62c9c2ba896e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Astro Data Fetching — Route-Level Loads That Kill Waterfalls$escape$,
  $escape$Astro's `getStaticProps`-equivalent lives inside `---` frontmatter for static pages, but for SSR routes (output: 'server'), data loading happens in the same frontmatter block — executed server-side before a single byte of HTML is streamed. This means zero client-side fetch waterfalls by design.

Inside `src/pages/posts/[slug].astro`, you call `Astro.params`, hit your DB or API, and pass data directly to the template — no useEffect, no loading spinner, no sequential fetches. For parallel data needs, use `Promise.all` in frontmatter: both queries fire simultaneously, and the page renders only after all data resolves.

Astro's middleware (`src/middleware.ts`) lets you attach data to `locals` before the page handler runs — useful for auth context or shared DB connections that every route needs. Access it via `Astro.locals` in any page.

Never reach for `fetch` inside an Astro component's template expression. That runs per-render without caching, defeats streaming, and reintroduces the waterfall. Keep all I/O in frontmatter or middleware — Astro enforces this naturally since component scripts don't have async lifecycle hooks.$escape$,
  $escape$---
// src/pages/posts/[slug].astro
import { db } from '@/lib/db';

const { slug } = Astro.params;

// Parallel fetch — no waterfall
const [post, related] = await Promise.all([
  db.post.findUnique({ where: { slug } }),
  db.post.findMany({ where: { tag: 'astro' }, take: 3 })
]);

if (!post) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---
<article>{post.title}</article>$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
