INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'df155a68-93d2-4fdb-a09d-bab732374b16',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Astro Error Handling: Custom 404 Pages, SSR Response Guards, and Redirects$escape$,
  $escape$Astro has no per-route error segments like Next.js's `error.tsx` or SvelteKit's `+error.svelte`. Error boundaries are global: place `src/pages/404.astro` and `src/pages/500.astro` in your pages directory — Astro's runtime renders them automatically when a matching HTTP status is returned.

For dynamic SSR routes, guard missing data by returning a `Response` directly from the frontmatter. `return new Response(null, { status: 404 })` triggers your `404.astro` — no helper function required. The same pattern works in `.ts`/`.js` API endpoints.

`Astro.redirect()` handles navigation cases — bouncing unauthenticated users, canonical slug migrations, or deprecated URLs. It defaults to `302`; use `301` for permanent moves that matter for SEO indexing.

Critical gotcha: `return new Response(...)` only works under `output: 'server'` or `output: 'hybrid'`. In fully static builds, Astro pre-renders a `404.html` at build time — you must configure your host (e.g., `staticwebapp.config.json` on Azure Static Web Apps, `_redirects` on Netlify) to serve it on unmatched routes.$escape$,
  $escape$---
// src/pages/blog/[slug].astro — requires output: 'server' or 'hybrid'
import { getEntry } from 'astro:content';

const { slug } = Astro.params;
const post = await getEntry('blog', slug!);

if (!post) {
  // Delegates rendering to src/pages/404.astro
  return new Response(null, { status: 404, statusText: 'Not Found' });
}

if (post.data.canonicalRedirect) {
  return Astro.redirect(post.data.canonicalRedirect, 301);
}
---
<article><h1>{post.data.title}</h1></article>$escape$,
