INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'd1ebbb86-5cf7-4189-b168-e2cc3d338361',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Astro Testing — Unit-Test Loaders and Actions, Then Validate Routes with Playwright$escape$,
  $escape$Astro's Content Layer loaders and server Actions are pure async functions — unit-test them with Vitest before touching a browser. For a custom loader, mock the `LoaderContext`: stub `store.set`, pass a real `Map` as `meta`, supply a `parseData` spy, and call `loader.load()` directly. This lets you verify ETag caching logic, data normalization, and `generateDigest` behavior with zero network calls and fast feedback.

For Actions, call the exported handler directly in Vitest. Because `defineAction` wraps a typed, Zod-validated handler, you can pass raw objects and assert on the return shape — no HTTP layer, no form encoding, no overhead.

Playwright fills the gap Vitest can't: full route flows where SSR, middleware, and Actions interact end-to-end. In `playwright.config.ts`, add a `webServer` block pointing to `astro dev --host` on port 4321. Navigate to a route, submit a `<form>` wired to an Action (e.g., `action={actions.subscribe}`), and assert on the resulting DOM. This chain — Vitest for logic, Playwright for routes — keeps unit tests fast and E2E tests meaningful.$escape$,
  $escape$// src/loaders/posts.test.ts
import { postsLoader } from "./posts";
import { vi, test, expect } from "vitest";

test("stores parsed entries and updates lastMod meta", async () => {
  const store = { set: vi.fn() };
  const meta = new Map<string, string>();
  const parseData = vi.fn(async ({ data }: any) => data);

  await postsLoader().load({
    store, meta, parseData,
    logger: { info: vi.fn(), warn: vi.fn(), error: vi.fn() },
  } as any);

  expect(store.set).toHaveBeenCalled();
  expect(meta.get("lastMod")).toBeTruthy();
});$escape$,
