INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e9ab9a82-7a38-4c76-8e56-533a8234db1b',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Astro Routing — Dynamic Segments, Catch-Alls, and What Doesn't Exist$escape$,
  $escape$Astro's `src/pages/` directory drives routing. Static files map 1:1 to URLs. Dynamic segments use bracket syntax — `[slug].astro` captures a single segment via `Astro.params.slug`. For SSG, pair it with `getStaticPaths()` returning `{ params }` objects; for SSR, read params directly and return a 404 response manually with `new Response(null, { status: 404 })`.

Catch-all routes (`[...slug].astro`) match zero or more segments. Pass `{ params: { slug: undefined } }` in `getStaticPaths()` to cover the base path (e.g. `/docs`), and `'api/endpoints'` to cover `/docs/api/endpoints`. At runtime `Astro.params.slug` is a raw string — split on `/` to get segments. It is never an array.

Specificity wins in conflicts: `posts/[slug].astro` always beats `[...slug].astro` for `/posts/hello`.

Astro has no intercepting or parallel routes — those are Next.js App Router constructs. For parallel UI concerns, use named slots: `<slot name="sidebar" />` in a shared layout achieves the same compositional result without any routing magic.$escape$,
  $escape$// src/pages/docs/[...slug].astro
---
import type { GetStaticPaths } from 'astro';

export const getStaticPaths: GetStaticPaths = () => [
  { params: { slug: undefined } },          // → /docs
  { params: { slug: 'intro' } },            // → /docs/intro
  { params: { slug: 'api/endpoints' } },    // → /docs/api/endpoints
];

const { slug } = Astro.params;
const crumbs = slug?.split('/') ?? [];
---
<nav>{crumbs.map((c) => <span>{c} / </span>)}</nav>$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
