INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '91a63cd2-996f-4f45-8501-8f68b89624f7',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Astro i18n Routing — URL Prefixes, Cookies, and Server-Side Locale Detection$escape$,
  $escape$Astro 4.x ships built-in i18n routing via the `i18n` config key. Set `defaultLocale` and `locales`, then pick a strategy: `"pathname"` (default) prefixes non-default locales in the URL (`/fr/blog`), while `"domains"` maps locales to full domain names.

For URL-based routing, `prefixDefaultLocale: true` forces `/en/` on the default locale too — critical for clean canonicals and avoiding duplicate-content penalties. Your `src/pages/` tree mirrors the URL: `src/pages/en/`, `src/pages/fr/`.

On the server side, `Astro.currentLocale` gives the active locale derived from the URL segment. For first-visit auto-redirect, `Astro.preferredLocale` parses the `Accept-Language` header and matches it against your configured locales. `Astro.preferredLocaleList` returns the full ranked list for granular fallback logic.

Cookie-based locale sits outside Astro's native i18n — handle it in `src/middleware.ts` using `context.cookies.get('locale')` before the route resolves. Priority chain: cookie (user's explicit choice) → `preferredLocale` (header-derived, first visit) → `defaultLocale`. This keeps UX consistent without client-side flicker.$escape$,
  $escape$// astro.config.mjs
export default defineConfig({
  i18n: {
    defaultLocale: 'en',
    locales: ['en', 'fr', 'de'],
    routing: { prefixDefaultLocale: true },
  },
});

// src/middleware.ts
export const onRequest = defineMiddleware((ctx, next) => {
  const locale = ctx.cookies.get('locale')?.value
    ?? ctx.preferredLocale
    ?? 'en';
  if (ctx.url.pathname === '/') return ctx.redirect(`/${locale}/`);
  return next();
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
